extends template.pug

block info
    - var main_title = "Packet Sniffing Backdoor"    
    - var sub_title = "Establish a communication channel between a victim's machine and a attacker's machine"
    - var banner = "../assets/img/packet-sniffing-backdoor/banner.jpg"
    - var date = "October 30, 2020"

block content
    article
        .container
            .row
                .col-lg-8.col-md-10.mx-auto
                    h2.section-heading Objective
                    p
                        | Design and implement a packet sniffing backdoor. The 
                        | backdoor is essentially a communication channel between
                        | a victim's machine and a attacker's machine

                    h2.section-heading Constraint
                    ul
                        li 
                            | The backdoor must camouflage itself so as to deceive
                            | anyone looking at the process table
                        li
                            | The backdoor must ensure that it only receives (authenticate)
                            | those packets that are meant for the backdoor itself
                        li
                            | The backdoor must interpret commands sent to it and execute
                            | them and send the results back.
                        li
                            | Incorporate and encryption scheme into the backdoor
                        
                    h2.section-heading Approach
                    p
                        | We will use the c library #[strong libpacp] to implement the
                        | backdoor. To make the process of communicating with the backdoor
                        | more intuitive, we will also write a remote access client. To issue
                        | a command to the backdoor, the remote client will send a UDP packet
                        | to the backdoor. The payload of that packet has a predefined keyword
                        | followed by a ciphertext of the actual command to be executed on the
                        | backdoor. The key used to create the ciphertext is shared with the 
                        | backdoor program.
                    
                    p
                        | Network trafiic capturing happens before the firewall, therefore, 
                        | the backdoor will still be able to sniff the incoming packet even
                        | if there's a blocking rule in place. When the backdoor receives the
                        | UDP packet, it will check the keyword in the payload to verify that
                        | the packet is indeed from the remote client. Next, it will proceed to 
                        | decrypt the encrypted command, execute the command, and send the output
                        | of the command back to the remote client over TCP. The figures below show
                        | a sample of the UDP payload, and a high level overview of the communication
                        | process.

                    img.img-fluid(src="../assets/img/packet-sniffing-backdoor/payload-format.jpg", alt='...')
                    img.img-fluid(src="../assets/img/packet-sniffing-backdoor/communication-process.jpg", alt='...')

                    h2.section-heading Application design
                    p
                        | #[strong Modules]
                    p
                        | The backdoor has four component, #[strong backdoor.c], #[strong packet_handler.c], 
                        | #[strong tcp_sender.c] and #[strong config.h]
                    ul
                        li
                            | #[strong backdoor.c] - program entry point. Responsible for running packet sniffing.
                            | Has a callback function that invokes the packet handling function (in #[strong packet_handler.c])
                            | and command result returning function (in #[strong tcp_sender.c])
                        li
                            | #[strong packet_handler.c] - consists of a single function packet_handler(). The function
                            | is responsible for three things: determining whether the sniffed packet is for the 
                            | backdoor or not, executing the received command, and writing the result of the command
                            | execution to a temporary file.
                        li 
                            | #[strong tcp_sender.c] - consists of a single function send_output(). The function establishes
                            | TCP connection back to the remote client, and sends the content of the temporary file back
                            | to the remote client. The temporary is generated by the packet handler.
                        li
                            | #[strong config.h] - some defined constants, important ones including
                            ul 
                                li #[strong BACKDOOR_HEADER_KEY] - keyword for identifying packet for backdoor
                                li #[strong PASSWORD] - use for data encryption
                                li #[strong SNIFFER_FILTER] - filter to apply when using the pcap functions
                                li #[strong CLIENT_IP] - remote client ip
                                li #[strong CLIENT_PORT] - remote client tcp listening port
                        
                    p
                        | The remote client has two component, client.c and config.h
                    ul
                        li
                            | #[strong client.c] - program entry point. Responsible for sending commands to the
                            | backdoor, and listening for result return from backdoor
                        li
                            | #[strong config.h] - some defined constants, important ones including
                            ul 
                                li #[strong BACKDOOR_HEADER_KEY] - keyword for indentifying packet for backdoor
                                li #[strong PASSWORD] - use for data encryption
                                li #[strong SEND_PORT] - the port that backdoor is sniffing on
                                li #[strong CLIENT_PORT] - tcp listening port, for reading result
                                li #[strong BACKDOOR_IP] - ip of the machine running backdoor

                    h2.section-heading State machine
                    img.img-fluid(src="../assets/img/packet-sniffing-backdoor/state-machine-1.jpg", alt='...')
                    img.img-fluid(src="../assets/img/packet-sniffing-backdoor/state-machine-2.jpg", alt='...')
                
                    h2.section-heading Pseudo implementation
                    p (* blue is defined constant in config.h, green is the module)
                    img.img-fluid(src="../assets/img/packet-sniffing-backdoor/pseudo-1.jpg", alt='...')
                    img.img-fluid(src="../assets/img/packet-sniffing-backdoor/pseudo-2.jpg", alt='...')
                    img.img-fluid(src="../assets/img/packet-sniffing-backdoor/pseudo-3.jpg", alt='...')

                    h2.section-heading Usage
                    p
                        | #[strong Step 1]
                        br
                        | Open the #[strong config.h] in backdoor folder, edit the value of following constant:
                    ul
                        li #[strong BACKDOOR_HEADER_KEY] - key to authenticate the packet
                        li #[strong BACKDOOR_HEADER_LEN] - length of the header key
                        li #[strong PASSWORD] - password for encrypting execution result before sending back
                        li #[strong PASSLEN] - length of the password
                        li #[strong SNIFFER_FILTER] - pcap filter (e.g. "udp dst port 54")
                        li #[strong NIC_NAME] - name of the network interface to sniff on

                    p
                        | #[strong Step 2]
                        br
                        | Open the config.h in remote_client folder, edit the value of following constant:
                    ul 
                        li #[strong BACKDOOR_HEADER_KEY] - key to authenticate the packet
                        li #[strong BACKDOOR_HEADER_LEN] - length of the header key
                        li #[strong PASSWORD] - password for encrypting execution result before sending back
                        li #[strong PASSLEN] - length of the password
                        li #[strong BACKDOOR_PORT] - port number the backdoor is sniffing on
                        li #[strong CLIENT_PORT] - tcp port to listen on, for receiving result from backdoor
                        li #[strong BACKDOOR_IP] - ip of the machine running backdoor

                    p
                        | #[strong Step 3]
                        br
                        | To run the backdoor in a termianl, cd into the backdoor folder. Then run "make all"div
                        | The Makefile will compile, clean and automatically run the executable.
                        br
                        | To run the remote client in a terminal, cd into the backdoor folder, then run "make all".
                        | The Makefile will compile, clean and automatically run the executable. The terminal should
                        | prompt you for input. Type a command and press enter (e.g. ifconfig). If all things are 
                        | configured correctly, and the backdoor is running, the terminal running remote client
                        | should receive the same result return from the backdoor.

                    h2.section-heading Source code
                    p
                        | The project source code can be found 
                        a(href='https://github.com/ericwu1997/packet-sniffing-backdoor' style="color:blue;") here
                        |.

                    h2.section-heading Testing
                    img.img-fluid(src="../assets/img/packet-sniffing-backdoor/test-cases.jpg", alt='...')



                        